<WRITING SEX="FEMALE" PERSON="BRWWRITER"><ORLANDOHEADER TYPE="text"><FILEDESC><TITLESTMT><DOCTITLE>Katherine Cecil Thurston: writing</DOCTITLE></TITLESTMT><PUBLICATIONSTMT><AUTHORITY>Orlando Project</AUTHORITY></PUBLICATIONSTMT><SOURCEDESC>Based on original research by members of the Orlando Project.</SOURCEDESC></FILEDESC><REVISIONDESC><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MPO" WORKSTATUS="SUB" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>13 October 2010</DATE><ITEM>Initial document given to tagger.</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="JSE" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>25 November 2010</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="JSE" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>12 May 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="JSE" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>16 May 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="JSE" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>19 May 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="JSE" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>19 May 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="JSE" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>19 May 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="JSE" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>20 May 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="JSE" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>23 May 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="CFT" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>24 May 2011</DATE><ITEM>cft c</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="JSE" WORKSTATUS="REV" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>24 May 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MKD" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>25 May 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MKD" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>26 May 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MKD" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>27 May 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="JSE" WORKSTATUS="REV" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>31 May 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MPO" WORKSTATUS="CFB" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>2 June 2011</DATE><ITEM>cfb c</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MPO" WORKSTATUS="CFT" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>2 June 2011</DATE><ITEM>cft, cfb c, pilot42</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="REV" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>3 June 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="PUB" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>5 June 2011</DATE><ITEM>pub i</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="SIB" WORKSTATUS="RBV" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>5 June 2011</DATE><ITEM>rbv c</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY WORKSTATUS="pub" RESP="MPO" WORKVALUE="c"><DATE>21 June 2011</DATE><ITEM>pub c, pilot42</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY></REVISIONDESC></ORLANDOHEADER><DIV0><HEADING>Writing</HEADING><STANDARD>Thurston, Katherine Cecil</STANDARD><AUTHORSUMMARY><SHORTPROSE><P><GENERICRANGE>KCT, often forgotten today, was a highly popular and successful writer of <TGENRE GENRENAME="SHORTSTORY">short stories</TGENRE> and <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novels</TGENRE> at the beginning of the twentieth century. In 1904, she was propelled to literary fame and fortune with her wildly successful book <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">John Chilcote, MP</TITLE> (entitled <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC" REG="John Chilcote, MP">The Masquerader</TITLE> in America), a sensational tale of political impersonation, which was made into two successful plays and later two films (one silent).</GENERICRANGE> This earned her an avid following, allowing her to experiment in her subsequent novels with more radical subject matter&mdash;including gambling, suicide, adultery, and the homoerotic&mdash;until her untimely death at the age of thirty-six. Her characteristic tone is thrilling, melodramatic, and often playfully sensational.</P></SHORTPROSE></AUTHORSUMMARY><DIV1><HEADING>Beginnings</HEADING><DIV2><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P><PFIRSTLITERARYACTIVITY>KCT began writing seriously shortly after her marriage, with the encouragement of her husband, writer <NAME STANDARD="Thurston, Ernest Temple">E. Temple Thurston</NAME>. She was then in her mid-twenties.</PFIRSTLITERARYACTIVITY><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="The Bookman 23.138 (March 1903): 227" DBREF="64007">23.138 (March 1903): 227</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Before her marriage, <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">the idea of writing [a book] never crossed her mind,</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="The Bookman 23.138 (March 1903): 227" DBREF="64007">23.138 (March 1903): 227</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> though she had already tried unsuccessfully to publish at least one short story.</P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION></DIV2></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Periodical Publications and Short Fiction</HEADING><DIV2><HEADING><TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">Masquerade</TITLE></HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="67830" PLACEHOLDER="KCT, &apos;Masquerade.&apos; The Pall Mall Magazine 24.100 (August 1901): 571-"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="MPO" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE"><DATE VALUE="1901-04-">April 1901</DATE><CHRONPROSE><PPERIODICALPUBLICATION><PSUBMISSIONSREJECTIONS>After trying for a year, KCT had her first finished work (a <TGENRE GENRENAME="SHORTSTORY">short story</TGENRE>, <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">Masquerade</TITLE>, not to be confused with her popular novel <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC" REG="John Chilcote, MP">The Masquerader</TITLE>) accepted by the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Pall Mall Magazine</TITLE>.</PSUBMISSIONSREJECTIONS> It appeared in the next issue, in August.</PPERIODICALPUBLICATION></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="The Bookman 23.138 (March 1903): 228" DBREF="64007">23.138 (March 1903): 228</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="C19" DBREF="48826"></BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Thurston &apos;Masquerade.&apos; The Pall Mall Magazine 24.100 (August 1901): 571" DBREF="67830">24.100 (August 1901): 571</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><TPLOT>The appropriately titled three-page story tells the tale of a couple who meet at a <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="masquerade">Masquerade</TMOTIF> Ball only to discover, when masks are thrown aside, that each has found their long-lost lover, carelessly driven away five years before.</TPLOT> The story deals with a recurrent theme in KCT&apos;s body of work: that of <TTHEMETOPIC>hidden, reinvented, or misplaced <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="mistaken identity">identity</TMOTIF></TTHEMETOPIC>.</P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES></DIV2><DIV2><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P>The story appears not to have been reviewed.</P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2><DIV2><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P><PPERIODICALPUBLICATION>After this first publication, KCT contributed several further items to the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Pall Mall Magazine</TITLE>, as well as to <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL" REG="Tatler, 1901 - 1940, The">The Tatler</TITLE>, <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Sketch</TITLE>, <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">The Living Age</TITLE>, and the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Eclectic Magazine of Foreign Literature</TITLE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="The Bookman 23.138 (March 1903): 228" DBREF="64007">23.138 (March 1903): 228</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="C19" DBREF="48826"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS> These included two popular stories entitled <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">The Climax</TITLE> and <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">An Oriental</TITLE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="C19" DBREF="48826"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PPERIODICALPUBLICATION></P><P><PSERIALIZATION>Most of KCT&apos;s novels were also serialized before they appeared in book form. These appeared in <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Blackwood&apos;s Edinburgh Magazine</TITLE>, the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Daily Mail</TITLE>, <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Lady&apos;s Realm</TITLE>, or <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Harper&apos;s Bazaar</TITLE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Athenaeum 4017 (22 October 1904): 546" DBREF="2043">4017 (22 October 1904): 546</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="C19" DBREF="48826"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PSERIALIZATION></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION></DIV2></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Novels</HEADING><DIV2><HEADING><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Circle</TITLE></HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="67705" PLACEHOLDER="KCT, The Circle, 1903"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="MPO" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE"><DATE VALUE="1903-01-24">24 January 1903</DATE><CHRONPROSE>KCT&apos;s first <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novel</TGENRE>, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Circle</TITLE>, appeared in London. <TTHEMETOPIC>It features a woman in an unconventional role: the <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="FEMALE">actress</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE></TTHEMETOPIC>.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Athenaeum 3926 (24 January 1903): 124" DBREF="2043">3926 (24 January 1903): 124</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="The Fly on the Wheel front matter" DBREF="67847">front matter</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P>It was published by <ORGNAME STANDARD="Blackwood,, Pillams and Wilson">William Blackwood and Sons</ORGNAME> in London, <PPLACEOFPUBLICATION>and a few weeks later appeared in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT REG="New York City">New York</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="New York"></REGION><GEOG REG="USA"></GEOG></PLACE>, published by <ORGNAME STANDARD="Dodd,, Mead,, and Co.">Dodd and Mead</ORGNAME>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Athenaeum 3926 (24 January 1903): 124" DBREF="2043">3926 (24 January 1903): 124</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="The Bookman 23.138 (March 1903): 228" DBREF="64007">23.138 (March 1903): 228</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> It had been slated to appear in the United States on 17 January, <PMANUSCRIPTHISTORY>but the proofs were stolen in a packet of mail, so its release was postponed until <DATE>9 February 1903</DATE>.</PMANUSCRIPTHISTORY><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="The Bookman 23.138 (March 1903): 228" DBREF="64007">23.138 (March 1903): 228</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PPLACEOFPUBLICATION></P><P><PRARITIESFEATURESDECORATIONS>The United States edition of the book contained illustrations by American artist <NAME STANDARD="Birch, Reginald B.">Reginald Birch</NAME>. Most of KCT&apos;s subsequent novels contained illustrations of some kind, a feature common to popular literature at the time.</PRARITIESFEATURESDECORATIONS><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="The Bookman 23.138 (March 1903): 228" DBREF="64007">23.138 (March 1903): 228</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="REAL">The story centres on heroine <TCHARACTERNAME>Anna Solny</TCHARACTERNAME>, the <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="FEMALE">daughter of a curio-shop keeper</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> called <TCHARACTERNAME>Old Solny</TCHARACTERNAME> (Nicholas Solinkoff), a <TCHARACTERIZATION>Russian Jew</TCHARACTERIZATION> who has immigrated to <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>London</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>.</TSETTINGPLACE> Anna has a <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">look quite in itself</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Thurston, The Circle 56" DBREF="67705">56</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> as well as <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">[i]nspiration . . . . The one thing to set a match to the world&mdash;the one thing that really lights.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Thurston, The Circle 57" DBREF="67705">57</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> By some stroke of chance, Anna&apos;s theatrical ability is discovered by <TCHARACTERNAME>Mrs Maxtead</TCHARACTERNAME>, a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>wealthy, indomitable young widow</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> who after her husband&apos;s death realizes that she has <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">a capacity all [her] own</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Thurston, The Circle 66" DBREF="67705">66</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> for helping <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">people to tolerable success.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Thurston, The Circle 67" DBREF="67705">67</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Finding that Anna has a gift for the stage&mdash;indeed, that she <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">will be the greatest <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="FEMALE">actress</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> [Mrs Maxtead has] ever known</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Thurston, The Circle 91" DBREF="67705">91</BIBCIT></BIBCITS>&mdash;<TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="REAL">Mrs Maxstead offers to provide Anna with a five-year education in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Paris</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="France"></GEOG></PLACE> if Anna will leave her father and her home</TSETTINGPLACE> and then, after her education is complete, hand over a substantial cut of her earnings for five years. Anna accepts, but only under some compulsion. She knows that doing this means that both her father and <TCHARACTERNAME>Johann</TCHARACTERNAME>, the <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>faithful and timid (but cowardly) cripple</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> who loves her, will be saddened, but they will be allowed to live in peace. Mrs Maxtead has the means to harm Johann if Anna refuses her. When Anna eventually returns home eight years later, <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="madness">her father has gone mad in his old age</TMOTIF> (he dies shortly thereafter), while Johann has remained loyal to her. <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="happy ending">Eventually Anna chooses to marry the lover she met in Paris, <TCHARACTERNAME>Maurice Stroke</TCHARACTERNAME>, a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>compassionate and kind American</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>, and the two offer the hand of friendship to Johann.</TMOTIF></P><P>Several themes in KCT&apos;s first novel continue to crop up throughout her work: the <TTHEMETOPIC>female heroine in an unconventional role</TTHEMETOPIC> (here the actress as <TTHEMETOPIC>woman artist</TTHEMETOPIC>), the <TTHEMETOPIC>heroine abroad</TTHEMETOPIC> (here in Paris), and <TTHEMETOPIC>the heroine masquerading as someone she is not</TTHEMETOPIC> (here Anna feels she <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">is masquerading in unfair success</QUOTE>).<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Thurston, The Circle 298" DBREF="67705">298</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL" GENDEREDRESPONSE="GENDEREDNO">A review in <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">The Academy</TITLE> was largely flattering. It found that the book <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">impresses the reader</QUOTE> in <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">the care, the elaboration of minor detail, [and] the genuine effort to present difficult situations and subtle moods</QUOTE>&mdash;yet the book was ultimately <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">one of disappointment</QUOTE> because it came so <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">near to being a fine performance</QUOTE> yet did not quite achieve it.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="The Academy 1604 (31 January 1903): 105" DBREF="38128">1604 (31 January 1903): 105</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> The reviewer took particular issue with the <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">remoteness</QUOTE> of the characters of Anna, Strode, Mrs Maxstead, and Anna&apos;s father. It found only Johann (<QUOTE DIRECT="Y">the cripple</QUOTE>) to be <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">human enough</QUOTE>: he was <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">the best character in the book.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="The Academy 1604 (31 January 1903): 105" DBREF="38128">1604 (31 January 1903): 105</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL" GENDEREDRESPONSE="GENDEREDYES">A shorter and generally more positive review appeared in the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Athen&aelig;um</TITLE>, which recommended the novel based on its original plot, its <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">carefully studied and yet natural</QUOTE> characters, and the fact that <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">the interest [is] well maintained to the end.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Athenaeum 3931 (28 February 1903): 269" DBREF="2043">3931 (28 February 1903): 269</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> It too, however, objected to the character of Mrs Maxstead, which it found <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">ridiculous</QUOTE> and <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">tiresome.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Athenaeum 3931 (28 February 1903): 269" DBREF="2043">3931 (28 February 1903): 269</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING>Fame and Fortune: <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">John Chilcote, MP</TITLE> or <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC" REG="John Chilcote, MP">The Masquerader</TITLE></HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="67710" PLACEHOLDER="KCT, The Masquerader 1904"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="MPO" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE"><DATE VALUE="1904-09-24" CERTAINTY="BY">By 24 September 1904</DATE><CHRONPROSE><RLANDMARKTEXT><PPLACEOFPUBLICATION>KCT&apos;s second <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novel</TGENRE>, a <TGENRE GENRENAME="POLITICALWRITING">political</TGENRE> <TGENRE GENRENAME="THRILLER">thriller</TGENRE>, appeared simultaneously in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>London</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> and <PLACE><SETTLEMENT REG="New York City">New York</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="New York"></REGION><GEOG REG="USA"></GEOG></PLACE> under different titles: <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">John Chilcote, MP</TITLE> in London and <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC" REG="John Chilcote, MP">The Masquerader</TITLE> in New York.</PPLACEOFPUBLICATION></RLANDMARKTEXT></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Saturday Review 98.2552 (24 September 1904): 406" DBREF="364">98.2552 (24 September 1904): 406</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Madden-Simpson 330" DBREF="67847">330</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="The Fly on the Wheel front matter" DBREF="67847">front matter</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P>It was published by <ORGNAME STANDARD="HarperCollins Publishing">Harper &amp; Brothers</ORGNAME> in both places.<SCHOLARNOTE><P>The notice in the <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Athen&aelig;um</TITLE> listed the publisher wrongly.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Athenaeum 4017 (22 October 1904): 546" DBREF="2043">4017 (22 October 1904): 546</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SCHOLARNOTE> <PSERIALIZATION FORMOFSERIALIZATION="PERIODICALFORM">Before it appeared in book form, it was serialized in Britain in <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Blackwood&apos;s Edinburgh Magazine</TITLE> and the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Daily Mail</TITLE>. It appeared in <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Blackwood&apos;s Edinburgh Magazine</TITLE> from <DATERANGE FROM="1904-01-" TO="1904-10-" EXACT="BOTH">January to October 1904</DATERANGE>, and in <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Harper&apos;s Bazaar</TITLE> in America from <DATERANGE FROM="1904-01-" TO="1904-12-" EXACT="BOTH">January to December 1904</DATERANGE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Athenaeum 4017 (22 October 1904): 546" DBREF="2043">4017 (22 October 1904): 546</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="C19" DBREF="48826"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PSERIALIZATION> Reports indicate that readers of <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Harper&apos;s Bazaar</TITLE> were so enamoured of the tale as a serial that they wrote to the editor in <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">a stream of letters</QUOTE> requesting advance information on its conclusion.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="The Fly on the Wheel front matter" DBREF="67847">front matter</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P><P><PCIRCULATION><PEARNINGS>In the <PLACE><GEOG>USA</GEOG></PLACE>, KCT earned an astonishing &dollar;47,153 (for 163,426 copies) of the novel in the first year of sales alone.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Newlin 84" DBREF="67829">84</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PEARNINGS> By February 1906 it was reported in Britain to have sold a quarter of a million copies.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="The Bookman 29.173 (February 1906): 192" DBREF="67831">29.173 (February 1906): 192</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PCIRCULATION></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P>The novel explores a theme central to KCT&apos;s work: that of <TTHEMETOPIC>hidden or reinvented identity</TTHEMETOPIC>, or the hero <TTHEMETOPIC><TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="disguise">masquerading</TMOTIF> as someone he is not</TTHEMETOPIC>. In this plot-driven <TGENRE GENRENAME="MELODRAMA">melodrama</TGENRE> with elements of sensationalism, <TCHARACTERNAME>John Loder</TCHARACTERNAME>, a studious and ambitious man with no prospects, is found to have an <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">extraordinary likeness</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Thurston, The Masquerader 10" DBREF="67710">10</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> to <TCHARACTERNAME>John Chilcote</TCHARACTERNAME>, a wealthy and once-promising <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>member of parliament</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> who is secretly enslaved to the habit of <TTHEMETOPIC>morphia</TTHEMETOPIC>. <TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="REAL" SETTINGCLASS="MIDDLECLASS">After the two meet in a thick London fog, Loder agrees for a handsome stipend <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="disguise">to live as Chilcote</TMOTIF> for a week or two at a time when it becomes <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">physically impossible</QUOTE> for the real Chilcote to <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">be at [his] post</QUOTE> because his habit has overpowered him.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Thurston, The Masquerader 48" DBREF="67710">48</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Loder subsequently takes up residence at Chilcote&apos;s home in <PLACE><ADDRESS><ADDRLINE>Grosvenor Square</ADDRLINE></ADDRESS><SETTLEMENT REG="London"></SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>, steps into his position as a member of parliament, and lives as Chilcote for several weeks.</TSETTINGPLACE> Chilcote, in the meantime, lives as Loder, satiating his desire for obscurity and abandoning himself to his habit. Loder&apos;s ambition, intelligence, and energy enable him to <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="mistaken identity">flourish in Chilcote&apos;s position</TMOTIF>, raising his stature both in the <ORGNAME STANDARD="House of Commons">House of Commons</ORGNAME> and at Grosvenor Square with his previously alienated wife, <TCHARACTERNAME REG="Chilcote, Eve">Eve</TCHARACTERNAME>. When Loder is suddenly called back to his old position at a most inopportune moment, <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">his first sensation was one of physical discomfort and unfamiliarity,</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Thurston, The Masquerader 115" DBREF="67710">115</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> since Chilcote&apos;s life has become more real to him than his own. He soon begins to see Chilcote&apos;s world as his.</P><P>Throughout the novel, Loder is presented as being the ideal version of Chilcote, or his more true and full self: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">The similarity between them as they faced each other seemed abnormal, defying even the closest scrutiny. And yet, so mysterious is Nature even in her lapses, they were subtly, indefinably different. Chilcote was Loder deprived of one essential; Loder, Chilcote with that essential bestowed. The difference lay neither in feature, in coloring, nor in height, but in that baffling, illusive inner illumination that some call individuality, and others soul.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Thurston, The Masquerader 60" DBREF="67710">60</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></QUOTE> The end of the novel, with Chilcote finally replaced by Loder both in his public and his private life, seems the natural and appropriate conclusion. The real Chilcote has died of a <TTHEMETOPIC>morphia overdose</TTHEMETOPIC> and is buried under Loder&apos;s name, while <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="marriage ending">Loder marries Eve</TMOTIF>, who has discovered his true identity and fallen in love with him.</P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P>The novel&apos;s financial success was matched by critical acclaim in England and across the Atlantic. <RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL" GENDEREDRESPONSE="GENDEREDYES">A review in the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Athen&aelig;um</TITLE> offered unmixed praise, calling it <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">one of the most notable novels of the year.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Athenaeum 4017 (22 October 1904): 546" DBREF="2043">4017 (22 October 1904): 546</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Rarely has a well-worn idea been treated with such boldness, originality, and power,</QUOTE> the reviewer declared. It took particular note of the <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">characterization of the two men, physically so alike, morally so different,</QUOTE> as well as of Chilcote&apos;s wife, who was, in the reviewer&apos;s estimation, <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">scarcely less interesting</QUOTE> than the main characters.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Athenaeum 4017 (22 October 1904): 546" DBREF="2043">4017 (22 October 1904): 546</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL" GENDEREDRESPONSE="GENDEREDYES"><TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">The Academy</TITLE>&apos;s review was nearly as glowing. This reviewer too found the theme <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">well-worn</QUOTE>, but its treatment both <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">unusual and striking.</QUOTE> The novel was commended for its <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">pointed and crisply clear</QUOTE> writing, its interest, <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">very well sustained,</QUOTE> and its <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">capitally told</QUOTE> story.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="The Academy 1692 (8 October 1904): 312" DBREF="38128">1692 (8 October 1904): 312</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P>As a testament to its enduring popularity, the novel was quickly translated to the stage with a script written by <NAME STANDARD="Thurston, Ernest Temple">E. Temple Thurston</NAME>. The following year, in 1905, this play was produced and performed at <ORGNAME STANDARD="St James&apos;s Theatre">St James&apos;s Theatre</ORGNAME> in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>London</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="The Fly on the Wheel front matter" DBREF="67847">front matter</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Later, in 1917, a different theatrical adaptation by <NAME STANDARD="Booth, John Hunter">John Hunter Booth</NAME> toured around the world and landed at the <ORGNAME STANDARD="Lyric Theatre,, New York">Lyric Theatre</ORGNAME>, <PLACE><SETTLEMENT REG="New York City">New York</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="New York"></REGION><GEOG REG="USA"></GEOG></PLACE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="New York Times (12 March 1933): X3" DBREF="67865">(12 March 1933): X3</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> This play was subsequently made into a silent film in 1922.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="New York Times (12 March 1933): X3" DBREF="67865">(12 March 1933): X3</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="The Fly on the Wheel, front matter" DBREF="67847">front matter</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> In 1933 another film was made, this time with sound.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="New York Times (23 October 1932): X5" DBREF="67848">(23 October 1932): X5</BIBCIT></BIBCITS><RESEARCHNOTE>sib to img when doing final readthrough: don&apos;t we have a tag for all this kind of thing? rfictionalization?</RESEARCHNOTE></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Gambler</TITLE></HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="67707" PLACEHOLDER="KCT, The Gambler, 1905"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="MPO" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="DECADE"><DATE VALUE="1906-02-17" CERTAINTY="BY">By 17 February 1906</DATE><CHRONPROSE><PSERIALIZATION FORMOFSERIALIZATION="PERIODICALFORM">KCT&apos;s <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novel</TGENRE> <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Gambler</TITLE> was published in book form by <ORGNAME STANDARD="Hutchinson">John Hutchinson</ORGNAME>, having been first serialized in <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Lady&apos;s Realm</TITLE> from May 1905.</PSERIALIZATION></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="C19" DBREF="48826"></BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="The Bookman 29.173 (February 1906): 192" DBREF="67831">29.173 (February 1906): 192</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Athenaeum 4086 (17 February 1906): 199" DBREF="2043">4086 (17 February 1906): 199</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P>The book appeared on the back of the success of  <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">John Chilcote, MP</TITLE>. <PCIRCULATION>It was published immediately after sales of that novel reached a quarter of a million copies.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="The Bookman 29.173 (February 1906): 192" DBREF="67831">29.173 (February 1906): 192</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Gambler</TITLE>, however, was wildly popular on its own merits, reaching sales of thirty thousand copies within just a few weeks of its publication.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Review of Reviews 33.195 (March 1906): 314" DBREF="45706">33.195 (March 1906): 314</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PCIRCULATION></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P>Like KCT&apos;s other novels, this one is plot-driven with elements of <TGENRE GENRENAME="SENSATIONNOVEL">sensation</TGENRE> and <TGENRE GENRENAME="MELODRAMA">melodrama</TGENRE>, but it presents a new element in its prolonged examination of character. This places on view another aspect of KCT&apos;s skill as a writer: her ability to give characters psychological depth. Some themes from her previous works re-appear here: <TTHEMETOPIC><TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="gambling">the unconventional female heroine (this one is a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="FEMALE">gambler</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>)</TMOTIF>,</TTHEMETOPIC> and <TTHEMETOPIC>the woman abroad</TTHEMETOPIC> (this one travels to England, Italy, and other countries).</P><P><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Gambler</TITLE> was KCT&apos;s first to feature an <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>Irish</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> protagonist. This is <TCHARACTERNAME>Clodagh Asshlin</TCHARACTERNAME>, the daughter of an inveterate gambler. <TPLOT>In the first few chapters of the novel, a young Clodagh and her still younger sister <TCHARACTERNAME REG="Asshlin, Nance">Nance</TCHARACTERNAME> watch their father squander their entire savings and then die, <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="financial ruin">leaving the family in ruin</TMOTIF>. They are narrowly saved by his loyal friend, the English <TCHARACTERNAME>James Milbanke</TCHARACTERNAME>, a Casaubon-like figure nearly forty years Clodagh&apos;s senior, who offers her his hand in marriage as an honourable gesture. After a short time he dies, leaving Clodagh a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="FEMALE">young widow</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> with &pound;2,000 a year and few true friends. The rest of the story tells of Clodagh&apos;s own battle with gambling, as she is drawn into bad company and finds herself inexplicably attracted to the <TTHEMETOPIC>game of bridge</TTHEMETOPIC>, particularly as a means to forgetting the pain and anguish she has brought upon herself and caused to others. <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">[Clodagh&apos;s] own thoughts rode and spurred her, pressing her forward in a wild, panic-stricken search for oblivion. <QUOTE DIRECT="N">Come, Larry. Play! Play!</QUOTE> She paused and laughed, hysterically . . . <QUOTE DIRECT="N">I want to forget everything. Play! Play!</QUOTE></QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Thurston, The Gambler 477" DBREF="67707">477</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Clodagh herself avoids ruin for a second time only narrowly when her <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="female friendship">sister <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="secret">secretly</TMOTIF> arranges to pay her debts and clears up a misunderstanding with the one man who genuinely loves her</TMOTIF>, <TCHARACTERNAME>Walter Gore</TCHARACTERNAME>. <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="suicide">Ready to throw herself off a cliff</TMOTIF>, Clodagh receives a telegram from Gore explaining all, and the telegram&apos;s timely arrival, accompanied by a loyal servant and faithful pet dog, prevents her death. The novel concludes with her declaration that <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">There is a God, after all!</QUOTE>,<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Thurston, The Gambler 499" DBREF="67707">499</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> who has, perhaps, <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">saved worse</QUOTE> than herself.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Thurston, The Gambler 498" DBREF="67707">498</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TPLOT></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL" GENDEREDRESPONSE="GENDEREDYES"><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Gambler</TITLE> was widely and by and large favourably reviewed: in <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">The Academy</TITLE>, the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Athen&aelig;um</TITLE>, <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">The Bookman</TITLE>, the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Review of Reviews</TITLE>, and the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">English Illustrated Magazine</TITLE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="British Periodicals" DBREF="64007"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Though several critics spoke somewhat disparagingly of the novel&apos;s appeal to <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">the great mass of the novel-reading public,</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Review of Reviews 33.195 (March 1906): 314" DBREF="45706">33.195 (March 1906): 314</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> they commended KCT&apos;s <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">natural fluency in writing,</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Athenaeum 4088 (3 March 1906): 259" DBREF="2043">4088 (3 March 1906): 259</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> her ability to hold the reader&apos;s attention,<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Review of Reviews 33.195 (March 1906): 314" DBREF="45706">33.195 (March 1906): 314</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> her <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">portrayal of character,</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Athenaeum 4088 (3 March 1906): 259" DBREF="2043">4088 (3 March 1906): 259</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="REAL">and her <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">firm and vivid powers of description,</QUOTE> particularly of the <PLACE><GEOG REG="Ireland">Irish</GEOG> countryside</PLACE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="The Academy 1764 (24 February 1906): 181" DBREF="38128">1764 (24 February 1906): 181</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TSETTINGPLACE> </RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Mystics</TITLE></HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="67709" PLACEHOLDER="KCT, The Mystics, 1907"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="MPO" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="DECADE"><DATE VALUE="1907-04-04">4 April 1907</DATE><CHRONPROSE>KCT&apos;s <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Mystics</TITLE> appeared, to poor reviews. This short <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novel</TGENRE> tells the tale of a religious sect, and features one of Thurston&apos;s favourite themes: <TTHEMETOPIC>impersonation</TTHEMETOPIC>.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Athenaeum 4144 (30 March 1907): 393" DBREF="2043">4144 (30 March 1907): 393</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P><PSERIALIZATION FORMOFSERIALIZATION="PERIODICALFORM">The book had been serialized in <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Blackwood&apos;s Edinburgh Magazine</TITLE> from <DATERANGE FROM="1905-01-" TO="1905-05-" EXACT="BOTH">January to May 1905</DATERANGE></PSERIALIZATION>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="C19" DBREF="48826"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><TPLOT>The protagonist of <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Mystics</TITLE>, <TCHARACTERNAME>John Henderson</TCHARACTERNAME>, dupes a <TTHEMETOPIC>religious sect</TTHEMETOPIC> into believing that he is their <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="MALE">Prophet</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> in order <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="inheritance">to gain the fortune left to the sect by his uncle, which he believes to be rightly his</TMOTIF>. Henderson has nearly reached his goal when he falls in love with one of the sect&apos;s devotees, <TCHARACTERNAME>Enid Witcherley</TCHARACTERNAME>, and his love prompts him to abandon his plot and admit he is a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="MALE">fraud</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>. The novel concludes with her declaration of love for him.</TPLOT></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL" GENDEREDRESPONSE="GENDEREDYES">This novel was badly received. A scathing notice in <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Saturday Review</TITLE>, for instance, omitted to summarize the plot or mention even one character, saying instead: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">There is not even sufficient character in the story to make criticism possible.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Saturday Review 103.2687 (27 April 1907): 529" DBREF="364">103.2687 (27 April 1907): 529</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> There was worse to come: the novel <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">produces on the unfortunate reviewer the mental equivalent to a meal made of thistledown&mdash;of stale thistledown&mdash;an indigestion of vapidity . . . One is capable only of wonder that it should ever have been written.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="The Saturday Review 103.2687 (27 April 1907): 529" DBREF="364">103.2687 (27 April 1907): 529</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> The review took particular issue with KCT&apos;s representation of her Mystics&mdash;the sect to which she gave no actual name. It complained that she <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">does not even take the trouble to account for [the Mystics] beyond accrediting the <SOCALLED>People</SOCALLED> with a Book, a Sign, a Sanctuary, and a vague craving for a Prophet.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="The Saturday Review 103.2687 (27 April 1907): 529" DBREF="364">103.2687 (27 April 1907): 529</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Fly on the Wheel</TITLE></HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="67706" PLACEHOLDER="KCT, The Fly on the Wheel, 1908"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="MPO" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE"><DATE VALUE="1908-03-28" CERTAINTY="BY">By 28 March 1908</DATE><CHRONPROSE><RBESTKNOWNWORK><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Fly on the Wheel</TITLE>, KCT&apos;s most <TGENRE GENRENAME="REALIST">realist</TGENRE> <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novel</TGENRE>, albeit with a sensationalist flavour, appeared in print. Uncanny similarities between the heroine&apos;s death and that, later, of the author&apos;s, helped to make it one of her best known works.</RBESTKNOWNWORK></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Athenaeum 4196 (28 March 1908): 380" DBREF="2043">4196 (28 March 1908): 380</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="OCLC" DBREF="1709"></BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Meaney 169" DBREF="51467">169</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P><PSERIALIZATION FORMOFSERIALIZATION="PERIODICALFORM">Like most of KCT&apos;s novels, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Fly on the Wheel</TITLE> was also first serialized. It appeared from <DATERANGE FROM="1907-10-" TO="1908-04-" EXACT="BOTH">October 1907 to April 1908</DATERANGE> in <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Blackwood&apos;s Edinburgh Magazine</TITLE>, and from <DATERANGE FROM="1908-02-" TO="1908-09-" EXACT="BOTH">February to September 1908</DATERANGE> in <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">The Bookman</TITLE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="C19" DBREF="48826"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PSERIALIZATION> <PEDITIONS>It is her only novel to have been reprinted since the early twentieth century (by <ORGNAME STANDARD="Virago Press">Virago Press</ORGNAME> in 1987).<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="OCLC" DBREF="1709"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PEDITIONS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P>According to critic <NAME STANDARD="Meaney, Gerardine">Gerardine Meaney</NAME>, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Fly on the Wheel</TITLE> offers <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">an exploration of the <TTHEMETOPIC>social and psychological restrictions on a young woman of independent mind in turn-of-the-century Irish society</TTHEMETOPIC>.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Meaney 169" DBREF="51467">169</BIBCIT></BIBCITS><TPLOT><TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="REAL"> Set in KCT&apos;s own environs, the town of <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Waterford</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Ardmore"></REGION> in <GEOG REG="Ireland">Ireland</GEOG></PLACE>, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Fly on the Wheel</TITLE> features <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="FEMALE">Irish</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> heroine <TCHARACTERNAME>Isabel Costello</TCHARACTERNAME>. She initially becomes engaged to the <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>struggling young doctor</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> <TCHARACTERNAME>Frank Carey</TCHARACTERNAME>,</TSETTINGPLACE> but they are prevented from marrying by financial considerations (Isabel has <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">nothing</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Thurston, The Fly on the Wheel 13" DBREF="67706">13</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> and is dependent on her aunt). She then falls in love instead with Frank&apos;s brother <TCHARACTERNAME>Stephan Carey</TCHARACTERNAME>, a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>successful <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">self-made</QUOTE> lawyer</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> and a typical middle-class hero <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">so far as middle-class Irish life produces heroes.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Thurston, The Fly on the Wheel 2" DBREF="67706">2</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Stephan, however, is already married with children. Although he promises to leave his wife, he eventually decides he cannot forfeit his life of middle-class respectability. The novel concludes with <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="death of heroine"><TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="suicide">Isabel&apos;s suicide</TMOTIF> by poison</TMOTIF> in a drawing room in <PLACE><REGION>Waterford</REGION><GEOG REG="Ireland"></GEOG></PLACE>.</TPLOT> <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="death of heroine">She chooses death because she cannot <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">be a man</QUOTE> even <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">for one hour</QUOTE>: all options are closed to her because she is a woman</TMOTIF>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Thurston, The Fly on the Wheel 315" DBREF="67706">315</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL" GENDEREDRESPONSE="GENDEREDYES">Initial reviews were positive. The <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Athen&aelig;um</TITLE>, for instance, considered the novel <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">a study of <TTHEMETOPIC>sexual passion</TTHEMETOPIC> rising at times to real power</QUOTE> and a <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">conscientious and clever piece of work.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Athenaeum 4196 (28 March 1908): 380" DBREF="2043">4196 (28 March 1908): 380</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="RE-EVALUATION" FORMALITY="FORMAL" GENDEREDRESPONSE="ADFEMINAM">The parallels with KCT&apos;s own death moved from the realm of rumour and speculation to become literary scholarship in 1916 when the story was reported by <NAME STANDARD="Brown, Stephen J.">Stephen Brown</NAME> in <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Ireland in Fiction</TITLE>. It has since been repeated both by <NAME STANDARD="Madden-Simpson, Janet">Janet Madden-Simpson</NAME> in her afterword to <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Fly on the Wheel</TITLE> (1987), and more recently by <NAME STANDARD="Meaney, Gerardine">Gerardine Meaney</NAME>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Meaney 169" DBREF="51467">169</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Madden-Simpson 330" DBREF="67847">330</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES> <RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="RE-EVALUATION" FORMALITY="INFORMAL" GENDEREDRESPONSE="ADFEMINAM"> The uncanny similarities between the heroine&apos;s death and KCT&apos;s own have fed the novel&apos;s popularity.</RRESPONSES></P><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="RE-EVALUATION" FORMALITY="FORMAL" GENDEREDRESPONSE="GENDEREDYES"><NAME STANDARD="Madden-Simpson, Janet">Madden-Simpson</NAME> has said that <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Fly on the Wheel</TITLE>, more than any of KCT&apos;s other novels, <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">is most dextrous in blending those two charactistic&mdash;and often warring&mdash;elements of her work: a flair for the dramatic and an abiding interest in psychology.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Madden-Simpson 331" DBREF="67847">331</BIBCIT></BIBCITS>The critic then goes on to suggest that the <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">questions of independence and power [that] lie at the centre of all Thurston&apos;s writing</QUOTE> are most <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">sensitively probed . . in <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Fly on the Wheel</TITLE>,</QUOTE> largely because this <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">novel . . was closest to Thurston&apos;s heart.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Madden-Simpson 331" DBREF="67847">331</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Max</TITLE></HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="67708" PLACEHOLDER="KCT, Max, 1910"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="MPO" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE"><DATE VALUE="1910-10-15" CERTAINTY="BY">By 15 October 1910</DATE><CHRONPROSE><PLASTLITERARYACTIVITY>KCT&apos;s <TOPIC STANDARD="New Woman">new-woman</TOPIC> <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novel</TGENRE> and final published work <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Max</TITLE> appeared in print, <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="cross-dressing">featuring a cross-dressing female heroine</TMOTIF> and a subtle <TTHEMETOPIC>exploration of the homoerotic</TTHEMETOPIC>.</PLASTLITERARYACTIVITY></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Meaney 170" DBREF="51467">170</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Athenaeum 4329 (15 October 1910): 454" DBREF="2043">4329 (15 October 1910): 454</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P><PSERIALIZATION FORMOFSERIALIZATION="PERIODICALFORM"><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Max</TITLE>&apos;s serialization in <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Harper&apos;s Bazaar</TITLE>, from <DATERANGE FROM="1910-03-" TO="1910-11-" EXACT="BOTH">March to November 1910</DATERANGE>, spanned the date of book publication.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="C19" DBREF="48826"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PSERIALIZATION></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P>The novel returns to a central theme in KCT&apos;s body of work, which by now had become a selling point for her: her focus on the <TTHEMETOPIC>prevalence of the <TMOTIF>masquerade</TMOTIF></TTHEMETOPIC>, <TMOTIF>disguise</TMOTIF>, and the <TTHEMETOPIC>reinvention of <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="mistaken identity">identity</TMOTIF></TTHEMETOPIC>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Meaney 170" DBREF="51467">170</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <NAME>Gerardine Meaney</NAME> specifically connects this freedom to reinvent the self with art and with <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">the release of a <TTHEMETOPIC>creativity</TTHEMETOPIC> more authentic than the accidents of society, sex, and personality which constitute one&apos;s <SOCALLED>real</SOCALLED> identity.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Meaney 170" DBREF="51467">170</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> The now familiar themes of the <TTHEMETOPIC>unconventional protagonist</TTHEMETOPIC> (here the <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="FEMALE">female artist</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>), and <TTHEMETOPIC>the protagonist abroad (here in Paris)</TTHEMETOPIC> assert themselves again.</P><P><TPLOT><TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="REAL" SETTINGCLASS="UPPERCLASS">The story concerns a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="FEMALE">young Russian noblewoman</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>, <TCHARACTERNAME REG="Max">Maxine</TCHARACTERNAME>, who absconds from <PLACE><GEOG CURRENT="Russian Federation" REG="Russia">Russia</GEOG></PLACE> to <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Paris</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="France"></GEOG></PLACE> to pursue a career as an artist and <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">to make a new life</QUOTE> for herself.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Thurston, Max 303" DBREF="67708">303</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TSETTINGPLACE> <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="loveless marriage">About to be trapped into a loveless marriage</TMOTIF>, <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="disguise">Maxine feels that her only option for freedom is to <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">ma[ke] [her]self a man,</QUOTE></TMOTIF> for <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">the world has made man the independent creature&mdash;and I desire <TTHEMETOPIC>independence</TTHEMETOPIC>.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Thurston, Max 303" DBREF="67708">303</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Living as a young man (the first half of the novel refers to Max as <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">he</QUOTE>, with few clues that <SOCALLED>he</SOCALLED> is actually a woman), Max meets and becomes friendly with a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="MALE">cosmopolitan Irishman</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>, <TCHARACTERNAME>Edward Blake</TCHARACTERNAME>. As Edward becomes increasingly confused about his feelings towards Max, Max attempts to expunge all signs of his/her <TTHEMETOPIC>femininity</TTHEMETOPIC> through art. The novel concludes as Max reveals himself as Maxine and the two admit their love for each other.</TPLOT></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P>Initial reviews of the novel were positive. <RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL">The <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Athen&aelig;um</TITLE>, for instance, commended the novel for its <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">atmosphere of youth and romance,</QUOTE> which the reviewer considered <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">comely and reviving, and the more so by reason of the author&apos;s admirably vivid impressions of the poetry of Paris and the <TTHEMETOPIC>glamour of <PLACE><SETTLEMENT CURRENT="Paris" REG="Montmartre"><SIC CORR="Montmartre">Montemartre</SIC></SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="France"></GEOG></PLACE></TTHEMETOPIC>.<RESEARCHNOTE>img: place tags by analogy with London districts</RESEARCHNOTE></QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Athenaeum 4329 (15 October 1910): 454" DBREF="2043">4329 (15 October 1910): 454</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="RECENT" FORMALITY="FORMAL" GENDEREDRESPONSE="GENDEREDYES">More recently, critic <NAME STANDARD="Meaney, Gerardine">Gerardine Meaney</NAME> has argued that the novel is both unique in its <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">exuberant gender play</QUOTE> and unmatched in its depiction of Irish culture <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">until <NAME STANDARD="Jordan, Neil">Neil Jordan</NAME>&apos;s <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Crying Game</TITLE></QUOTE> (a film made in 1992).<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Meaney 170" DBREF="51467">170</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="IMDb" DBREF="12265"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="RECENT" FORMALITY="FORMAL" GENDEREDRESPONSE="GENDEREDYES"><NAME STANDARD="Heilmann, Ann">Ann Heilmann</NAME> has noted, however, that the novel concludes as Max <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">forgets all about her painting career (her reason for impersonating a man) once she has married a colleague</QUOTE> and her <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">voluntary return to <SOCALLED>feminine</SOCALLED> occupations</QUOTE> has inevitable and <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">fatal consequences for [her] personal life.</QUOTE></RRESPONSES><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Heilmann 86" DBREF="67834">86</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING>Final Manuscript?</HEADING><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P>In the months before her death on <DATE VALUE="1911-09-05" CERTAINTY="BY">5 September 1911</DATE>, the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">New York Times</TITLE> reported that KCT was <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">much interested in an idea for a new book on which she will probably begin work in the summer.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="New York Times (29 January 1911): BR37" DBREF="67846">(29 January 1911): BR37</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> The manuscript, if one exists, remains unfound.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="New York Times (29 January 1911): BR37" DBREF="67846">(29 January 1911): BR37</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION></DIV2></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Reputation</HEADING><DIV2><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P>Despite her enormous popularity in the early twentieth century, KCT has largely faded from view today. Scant criticism exists on her work, and little biographical information has been found.</P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2></DIV1><WORKSCITED><SOURCE> Unless otherwise noted, all information is from the FC.</SOURCE><SOURCE> sample work cited</SOURCE></WORKSCITED></DIV0></WRITING>